  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States Approach\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Strong emphasis on financial institution reporting\n- Criminal and civil penalties\n- Extraterritorial enforcement capabilities\n\n2. European Union Approach\n- Unified AML Directive framework\n- Centralized regulatory standards\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Focus on international cooperation\n- Consistent cross-border implementation\n\n3. United Kingdom Model\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Risk-based supervisory framework\n- Sophisticated financial intelligence mechanisms\n- Strong international collaboration\n- Emphasis on financial sector transparency\n\n4. Swiss Approach\n- Traditionally more lenient banking secrecy laws\n- Increasing international compliance pressures\n- Gradual regulatory modernization\n- Enhanced transparency requirements\n\n5. Asian Jurisdictions\n- Varied approaches:\n- Singapore: Strict regulatory environment\n- Hong Kong: Robust compliance mechanisms\n- China: Centralized monitoring systems\n\n6. Emerging Market Approaches\n- Developing comprehensive legal frameworks\n- Implementing international standards\n- Increasing regulatory sophistication\n\nThese comparisons represent generalized perspectives on complex legal frameworks.",
